Dialogue: 0,0:02:13.55,0:02:16.17,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿Mother, let's have some tea.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:18.40,0:02:22.40,Default,,0,0,0,,Say, Mary... you aren't hiding anything from me, are you?
Dialogue: 0,0:02:23.64,0:02:26.54,Default,,0,0,0,,I have nothing to hide from you, mother!
Dialogue: 0,0:02:28.54,0:02:30.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Don't you really have some news?
Dialogue: 0,0:02:31.35,0:02:32.44,Default,,0,0,0,,News?﻿
Dialogue: 0,0:02:32.44,0:02:36.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Half a year passed since Arthur left the village with my grandchildren.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:36.42,0:02:40.86,Default,,0,0,0,,No, even seven months have passed. \NThey did it last August.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:40.86,0:02:41.96,Default,,0,0,0,,It is so.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:41.96,0:02:46.19,Default,,0,0,0,,The letter of them arriving to Australia was supposed to come long ago.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:46.54,0:02:51.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Mother! Did I not tell you \NEngland and Australia are very far apart?
Dialogue: 0,0:02:51.92,0:02:56.55,Default,,0,0,0,,The one is the edge of the Earth for the other. It's more than three months of sailing.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:56.55,0:02:58.09,Default,,0,0,0,,You keep saying that...
Dialogue: 0,0:03:03.04,0:03:06.56,Default,,0,0,0,,I hope news come soon of them arriving safely.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:13.02,0:03:15.32,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿It seems my husband is back.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:15.32,0:03:19.29,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿He was to town, right? \NI hope he figured to stop by the post office.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:19.29,0:03:20.39,Default,,0,0,0,,I guess he did{He should have been}.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:23.37,0:03:24.10,Default,,0,0,0,,It's cold!
Dialogue: 0,0:03:24.10,0:03:25.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Tonight it{[the snowdrift]} will definitely heap up{at this rate}!
Dialogue: 0,0:03:25.99,0:03:28.17,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿You didn't put the horse into the stable?
Dialogue: 0,0:03:28.64,0:03:33.01,Default,,0,0,0,,I will, naturally. But before that, \NI figured to give this to your mother.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:35.38,0:03:38.55,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, behold the long-awaited letter from Australia.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:38.55,0:03:40.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, mother!
Dialogue: 0,0:03:50.53,0:03:51.96,Default,,0,0,0,,Good Lord!
Dialogue: 0,0:03:57.32,0:03:58.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Read it for me, Mary.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:58.87,0:04:00.94,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿I have some kind of inexplicable fear. {I'm somehow frightened by it.}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:00.94,0:04:03.30,Default,,0,0,0,,I don't think there is anything to fear of.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:04.47,0:04:06.91,Default,,0,0,0,,It was Clara who wrote this letter!
Dialogue: 0,0:04:06.91,0:04:10.58,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿She turned sixteen while onboard the ship.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:13.58,0:04:14.98,Default,,0,0,0,,I'm reading, mother.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:15.65,0:04:20.17,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿"Grandma, aunt Mary, and finally, uncle Fred, how are you?
Dialogue: 0,0:04:20.17,0:04:24.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Our family has made it to South Australia.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:24.56,0:04:30.17,Default,,0,0,0,,We spent ninety five days aboard \Nuntil we could at last tread the soil again.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:30.17,0:04:34.74,Default,,0,0,0,,We have been trapped in the confined cabin \Nfor over three months.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:34.74,0:04:40.71,Default,,0,0,0,,To determine the order of passengers going ashore by boat, we drew lots." {Rephrase?}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:41.54,0:04:43.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Boat preparations are finished! {They use formal sailor code}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:43.28,0:04:45.88,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿Okay! Next group, please.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:45.88,0:04:47.25,Default,,0,0,0,,That would be us.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:49.25,0:04:51.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's go, sis. \NI'll lend you a shoulder.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:51.65,0:04:52.55,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿Thank you, Ben.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:52.55,0:04:54.06,Default,,0,0,0,,No, you're waiting. {No, you wait.}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:54.06,0:04:56.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Our family goes ahead. {Our family leaves first.}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:56.09,0:05:01.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Excuse me, Mr. Pettywell, but the lots we've drawn{previously} say it's our turn now.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:01.80,0:05:06.47,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿My wife's state is deteriorating.{My wife is not feeling well.} She cannot comply with that order. {She is not waiting for our turn.}{I don't wanna use 'turn' in two sentences in a row and what he says is literally 'Not waiting for order'}
Dialogue: 0,0:05:06.47,0:05:07.40,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿Now, let us go.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:08.64,0:05:10.91,Default,,0,0,0,,As well as my daughter's state.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:10.91,0:05:13.24,Default,,0,0,0,,My family is different from yours. {We are not the same kind of people.}
Dialogue: 0,0:05:13.24,0:05:16.65,Default,,0,0,0,,I paid a fortune in fares for taking this ship all the way from England. {Trying to make it sound as if the ship would have never left the harbor without him onboard.}
Dialogue: 0,0:05:16.65,0:05:19.35,Default,,0,0,0,,Naturally, this includes my wife and servants as well.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:19.35,0:05:23.49,Default,,0,0,0,,I have a privilege over those \Nwho came here on government expense.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:23.75,0:05:25.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Is that so, boy?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:26.45,0:05:27.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah...
Dialogue: 0,0:05:27.29,0:05:29.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Make sure you don't forget any luggage.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:41.67,0:05:43.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Can't be helped. \NWe'll wait for the next.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:43.61,0:05:44.77,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿What a rotten person!
Dialogue: 0,0:05:44.77,0:05:45.34,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿Kate...
Dialogue: 0,0:05:45.34,0:05:48.71,Default,,0,0,0,,How can I not say it \Nif Mr. Pettywell is such a rotten person?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:48.71,0:05:50.51,Default,,0,0,0,,I thought so before too. {I knew that for a long time.}
Dialogue: 0,0:05:50.51,0:05:52.25,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿Be quiet, Kate.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:52.25,0:05:57.42,Default,,0,0,0,,What now? He queue-jumped in front of us. Can't even make fun of his pompousness! {He is so puffed up. It isn't even funny!}
Dialogue: 0,0:06:03.48,0:06:07.36,Default,,0,0,0,,That fellow Mosh{My guess is Mosh, a rare jewish name, abbreviation of Moses. Licca previously used the 'Marsh' transcription which seems totally plausible as well} is probably dying in there...
Dialogue: 0,0:06:07.36,0:06:09.45,Default,,0,0,0,,Why is he supposed to be dying?
Dialogue: 0,0:06:09.45,0:06:14.10,Default,,0,0,0,,You should know it yourself!\NHamsters hibernate during winter.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:14.10,0:06:18.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Back in England, the winter is already in full swing by now. \NBut here it's summer.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:18.87,0:06:23.13,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿Therefore, Mosh cannot hibernate and it drives him crazy, I believe.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:23.13,0:06:27.25,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿Mosh will be fine! Australia reinvigorated him!
Dialogue: 0,0:06:30.30,0:06:32.22,Default,,0,0,0,,Feeling better, sis?
Dialogue: 0,0:06:32.22,0:06:36.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, thank you. \NThe sea breeze reaches me even down here.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:36.16,0:06:40.73,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿Father yielded our turn to Mr. Pettywell for whatever reason.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:40.73,0:06:43.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Can't be helped. \NHe is rich{a moneybag} after all.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:43.57,0:06:51.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Why did we come all the way to South Australia then? \NFather told us this place is full of freedom and equality.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:56.31,0:07:03.02,Default,,0,0,0,,"Unfortunately, on the first day of landing, \NI was feeling a bit ill.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:03.65,0:07:05.09,Default,,0,0,0,,It must have been heat.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:09.82,0:07:12.09,Default,,0,0,0,,However, everyone else was in high spirits. {Maybe change to 'was feeling well.' to counterweight her sickness}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:12.56,0:07:16.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Especially Kate and Lucy-May, \Nwhose spirits were over the top.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:16.93,0:07:21.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Too enthusiastic about riding a boat, \NLucy-May tripped into the sea.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:23.21,0:07:27.31,Default,,0,0,0,,The one who followed Lucy-May to rescue her \Nwas a young sailor named John.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:27.98,0:07:32.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Throughout the voyage, \Nhe has been the most cordial{amiable} to us.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:33.55,0:07:35.82,Default,,0,0,0,,It's almost summer in these parts.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:35.82,0:07:40.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Thanks to that, Lucy-May never caught a cold \Nafter tumbling into the sea."
Dialogue: 0,0:07:41.92,0:07:44.49,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿Say, what is she talking about, Mary?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:44.49,0:07:45.92,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿What, Mother?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:45.92,0:07:51.93,Default,,0,0,0,,Here it's snowing all over the place, but in Australia they have summer?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:51.93,0:07:56.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Mother, winter and summer periods in Australia \Nare reversed in regard to England.{Mother, winter and summer periods in Australia are opposed to the ones in England.}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:56.44,0:07:57.54,Default,,0,0,0,,How come?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:57.54,0:07:59.41,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿It's on the southern side of the globe.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:59.41,0:08:02.41,Default,,0,0,0,,How does the southern side explain the seasons reversed?
Dialogue: 0,0:08:03.88,0:08:06.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Even I don't know everything.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:07.62,0:08:09.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Winter and summer reversed, then?
Dialogue: 0,0:08:09.98,0:08:11.39,Default,,0,0,0,,I’m glad anyway.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:11.39,0:08:15.96,Default,,0,0,0,,At least the ship didn't sink on the way, \NI was so worried it would!
Dialogue: 0,0:08:15.96,0:08:20.43,Default,,0,0,0,,But the struggle{trouble} is still ahead.\N﻿They are now in a virtually uninhabited place.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:20.43,0:08:23.93,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿Everyone would have to blaze their own trail from here on.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:23.93,0:08:28.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Build lodgings and eventually towns. \NThen there are plots{farms} and pastures.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:29.44,0:08:33.14,Default,,0,0,0,,The worst part is, I'm never seeing my adorable grandchildren again.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:36.78,0:08:38.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Mother!
Dialogue: 0,0:08:43.05,0:08:45.82,Default,,0,0,0,,You two! Have I not told you not to stand up?
Dialogue: 0,0:08:52.69,0:08:57.17,Default,,0,0,0,,You two can't sit still, can you? \NThis time, no one is helping if you fall in the sea!
Dialogue: 0,0:08:57.17,0:08:58.40,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿Right, John?
Dialogue: 0,0:08:58.40,0:08:59.23,Default,,0,0,0,,Uh-huh.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:59.23,0:09:00.94,Default,,0,0,0,,Are you not cold, Lucy-May?
Dialogue: 0,0:09:01.54,0:09:03.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Not one bit! {No-no-no!}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:08.08,0:09:10.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Mosh is already fully dry!
Dialogue: 0,0:09:10.85,0:09:14.15,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿Those girls have not changed one bit \Nfrom what they were back home.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:14.15,0:09:16.05,Default,,0,0,0,,They are the most buoyant.{They are the cheerfulness embodied.}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:16.05,0:09:18.15,Default,,0,0,0,,I am only a bit worried about Clara. {Only Clara is worried about them.}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:19.35,0:09:22.52,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿By the way, what is the plan after we are ashore?
Dialogue: 0,0:09:22.52,0:09:26.23,Default,,0,0,0,,To begin with, we will arrange sleeping quarters in the vicinity.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:26.23,0:09:28.15,Default,,0,0,0,,There, you can see it yourself.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:28.15,0:09:30.60,Default,,0,0,0,,There are such camps all over the place.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:34.70,0:09:37.27,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿Is that where Adelaide is?
Dialogue: 0,0:09:37.27,0:09:40.70,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿No, the city sits in some distance from the shore.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:40.70,0:09:44.21,Default,,0,0,0,,South Australia capital is Adelaide, is that so?
Dialogue: 0,0:09:45.11,0:09:49.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Even though it's the capital, it only has about 300 residents at the moment.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:11.74,0:10:12.91,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿Thank yon, John.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:26.69,0:10:29.12,Default,,0,0,0,,This is the land we spend the rest of our lives on.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:37.67,0:10:38.63,Default,,0,0,0,,It feels great!
Dialogue: 0,0:10:40.00,0:10:41.39,Default,,0,0,0,,So fun!
Dialogue: 0,0:10:41.39,0:10:44.40,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿It's Australia! \NIt's Australia for you! {It's Australia, everyone!}
Dialogue: 0,0:10:48.11,0:10:52.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, everyone! Take whatever you can carry. \NWe will unload it on top of that dune.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:52.90,0:10:53.85,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿Okay!
Dialogue: 0,0:10:56.22,0:10:59.86,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿Father, when are we retrieving \Nthe rest of our luggage from that ship?
Dialogue: 0,0:10:59.86,0:11:01.82,Default,,0,0,0,,I don't know yet.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:01.82,0:11:06.49,Default,,0,0,0,,There are only bulky pieces left, \Nso boats will have to bring them in several rounds.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:10.63,0:11:12.83,Default,,0,0,0,,I will be back!
Dialogue: 0,0:11:14.10,0:11:14.92,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿Clara.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:16.13,0:11:21.64,Default,,0,0,0,,You should not exert yourself since you have a fever. \NJust watch over Tob and our luggage.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:21.64,0:11:23.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Okay. I understand.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:49.70,0:11:55.58,Default,,0,0,0,,"While sitting there, thinking, I could appreciate, \Nto my surprise, how desolate is the surrounding scenery.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:56.74,0:12:02.22,Default,,0,0,0,,I couldn't help wondering \Nhow can human live in a place like that.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:03.45,0:12:05.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Still, I have to do my best.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:06.42,0:12:13.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Grandma, from now on, I will make sure to secure a letter for you whenever there's a ship returning to England.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:13.70,0:12:15.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Take care, and good bye.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:17.23,0:12:25.14,Default,,0,0,0,,November 7th, 1837, from South Australia, Clara Poppel."
Dialogue: 0,0:12:32.98,0:12:34.72,Default,,0,0,0,,It's summer over there...
Dialogue: 0,0:12:43.02,0:12:45.33,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿Now, hold it tight, Ben.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:45.33,0:12:45.86,Default,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:46.49,0:12:47.86,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿Heave-ho!
Dialogue: 0,0:13:00.61,0:13:02.54,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿Father, you are such a handyman.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:03.68,0:13:06.35,Default,,0,0,0,,Farmers have to be Jacks of all trades.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:11.55,0:13:13.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Where did mother go fetching the water?
Dialogue: 0,0:13:24.07,0:13:26.07,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿This is like a birds realm.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:56.73,0:13:57.36,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's go!
Dialogue: 0,0:14:10.01,0:14:14.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Look, over there! \NMr. Pettywell is building himself a house. {camp}
Dialogue: 0,0:14:14.60,0:14:20.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Alright, that much of driving it in should do fine. \NNow start pulling it on this side.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:20.61,0:14:23.73,Default,,0,0,0,,He could do some work himself, \Nnot just give orders!
Dialogue: 0,0:14:23.73,0:14:25.76,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿We have not been doing any work either.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:26.26,0:14:30.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Good point. How about we stop wandering around \Nand offer father some help?
Dialogue: 0,0:14:30.87,0:14:34.77,Default,,0,0,0,,I am little, so it is okay for me to be playing. \NBut you can help...
Dialogue: 0,0:14:34.77,0:14:38.44,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿Not happening! If I am going to work, \Nyou are working along with me.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:38.44,0:14:42.34,Default,,0,0,0,,Alright, that's enough. \NStart carrying our luggage into the tent, you two.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:42.34,0:14:43.04,Default,,0,0,0,,- Okay! \N- Okay.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:43.54,0:14:46.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Hurry up, you rascals! Hurry up! \NThe sun is about to set!
Dialogue: 0,0:15:02.13,0:15:03.36,Default,,0,0,0,,Why, you...
Dialogue: 0,0:15:13.41,0:15:17.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Why are you standing here looking at me idly, \Nyou blockheads?! Start by rebuilding it!
Dialogue: 0,0:15:17.88,0:15:22.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Until this is fixed, no one is getting their supper! \NGet to work, loafer breed! {sloth offspring!}
Dialogue: 0,0:15:25.75,0:15:29.09,Default,,0,0,0,,What are you doing in such a place? \NI have been looking for you!
Dialogue: 0,0:15:29.79,0:15:30.69,Default,,0,0,0,,Sis...
Dialogue: 0,0:15:31.13,0:15:32.43,Default,,0,0,0,,There... There!
Dialogue: 0,0:15:34.06,0:15:35.96,Default,,0,0,0,,And then "Slam!" {Lucy is onomatopoeing sounds of falling bomb and wind shutting the door here}
Dialogue: 0,0:15:52.55,0:15:53.95,Default,,0,0,0,,No playing around!
Dialogue: 0,0:15:54.38,0:15:59.45,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿I am not playing around!\NJust making sure it does not hurt when you use it!
Dialogue: 0,0:16:03.09,0:16:04.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Does not hurt, does not hurt!
Dialogue: 0,0:16:06.13,0:16:07.09,Default,,0,0,0,,I thought so!
Dialogue: 0,0:16:08.43,0:16:10.22,Default,,0,0,0,,Does not hurt, does not hurt!
Dialogue: 0,0:16:14.67,0:16:18.24,Default,,0,0,0,,What a smell! \NI am so hungry I just cannot stand it! {I'm so gungry it drives me crazy!}
Dialogue: 0,0:16:18.24,0:16:19.21,Default,,0,0,0,,So do I!
Dialogue: 0,0:16:21.71,0:16:23.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Mom!
Dialogue: 0,0:16:23.14,0:16:28.08,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿Please wait just a bit longer.\N﻿The salt pork soup is on the way.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:28.08,0:16:30.12,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿It needs some more seething.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:30.12,0:16:35.06,Default,,0,0,0,,Mom, we laid enough straw in the tent. \NYou can sleep well wherever you want.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:35.06,0:16:36.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Is that so?
Dialogue: 0,0:16:36.86,0:16:40.19,Default,,0,0,0,,Then could you go to Clara and Ben to tell them we don't need more?
Dialogue: 0,0:16:40.19,0:16:41.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Sure!
Dialogue: 0,0:16:47.80,0:16:50.24,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿Father is bringing along that thing.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:50.24,0:16:52.17,Default,,0,0,0,,My, that's a large barrel.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:58.71,0:17:04.52,Default,,0,0,0,,It was lying on the shore nearby. \NThe bottom is gone, so it's not gonna hold any more water.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:04.52,0:17:06.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Why did you bring it here, then?
Dialogue: 0,0:17:06.42,0:17:09.72,Default,,0,0,0,,That tent cannot accommodate us all sleeping in it.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:10.16,0:17:16.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Then, someone will be sleeping inside here? \NFather, who will be sleeping in it?
Dialogue: 0,0:17:17.10,0:17:18.70,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿Lucy, you want to sleep here?
Dialogue: 0,0:17:18.70,0:17:19.93,Default,,0,0,0,,Me?
Dialogue: 0,0:17:19.93,0:17:21.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Afraid to be here alone?
Dialogue: 0,0:17:22.24,0:17:23.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes...
Dialogue: 0,0:17:23.04,0:17:25.67,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿But together with sis, I will be fine.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:25.67,0:17:28.31,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿The two of you can sleep here no problem.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:28.31,0:17:31.55,Default,,0,0,0,,Maybe it would be better \Nif Ben sleeps here instead of girls?
Dialogue: 0,0:17:32.45,0:17:35.02,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿I want to sleep here!\NSis is back.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:35.55,0:17:36.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Sis!
Dialogue: 0,0:17:37.18,0:17:39.89,Default,,0,0,0,,We will be sleeping inside a barrel!
Dialogue: 0,0:17:39.89,0:17:41.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Inside a barrel?
Dialogue: 0,0:17:41.31,0:17:43.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes!\NLet me have that straw.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:44.96,0:17:47.40,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿Mother, did you say the tent interior is done?
Dialogue: 0,0:17:47.40,0:17:52.07,Default,,0,0,0,,You did well. \NPlease lay the remaining straw inside this barrel.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:52.07,0:17:53.07,Default,,0,0,0,,Inside the barrel?
Dialogue: 0,0:17:53.07,0:17:56.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Me and sis are now sleeping in here!
Dialogue: 0,0:18:00.21,0:18:01.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Are you sure, mom?
Dialogue: 0,0:18:02.18,0:18:04.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, we're still to hear what Kate says.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:09.68,0:18:14.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Of course, I will sleep here!﻿ \NSleeping in a barrel must be lovely!
Dialogue: 0,0:18:15.12,0:18:16.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Let me have that straw.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:17.83,0:18:20.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Here! Let me finish the bed for us!
Dialogue: 0,0:18:21.43,0:18:24.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Sister, you are mean, mean, mean beyond belief!
Dialogue: 0,0:18:25.80,0:18:29.23,Default,,0,0,0,,Dad, they should sleep here instead of me. \NThis way I feel relieved.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:30.67,0:18:32.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Your mother said so too.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:32.61,0:18:36.38,Default,,0,0,0,,That's right. In such a place, \Nthose two can brawl all they want. {Okay, for the first time, I'm lost here. He says 'Presence of those two together in such a place is a source of quarrel' but I, for the life of it, am not tuning in how this can be turned to sound wholesome - TL}
Dialogue: 0,0:18:36.84,0:18:37.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Right, mom?
Dialogue: 0,0:18:37.88,0:18:39.20,Default,,0,0,0,,I guess...
Dialogue: 0,0:18:39.20,0:18:42.72,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿We are sleeping in the barrel!
Dialogue: 0,0:19:29.76,0:19:33.93,Default,,0,0,0,,Before we proceed to eating, \NI have something to say to all of you.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:33.93,0:19:36.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Aside from Tob, \Nwho probably won't understand a word of it,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:37.51,0:19:40.34,Default,,0,0,0,,I want everyone to listen closely to what I say.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:41.24,0:19:45.65,Default,,0,0,0,,We have all made it to Australia safe and sound.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:45.65,0:19:49.02,Default,,0,0,0,,You are all well aware of my purpose for coming here —
Dialogue: 0,0:19:49.02,0:19:53.25,Default,,0,0,0,,to build a farm much bigger \Nthan the farm we had back in England.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:53.25,0:19:55.29,Default,,0,0,0,,And I'm sure it won't take long.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:55.29,0:20:00.63,Default,,0,0,0,,But until that happens, I want everyone \Nto endure bravely all the hardships that we are to face.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:01.66,0:20:05.17,Default,,0,0,0,,After all, we are not staying in this area forever.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:05.87,0:20:09.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Tomorrow or the day after that, I'm walking to Adelaide.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:09.84,0:20:13.44,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿Adelaide is about 10 kilometers inwards from this shore. {I abriged this to the utmost, but it's still too bulky}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:14.48,0:20:20.75,Default,,0,0,0,,A capital of South Australia, it is now being erected as a glorious city, devoid of any disgraceful stains.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:21.18,0:20:27.68,Default,,0,0,0,,With the parts I brought from England, I am planning to build a magnificent{He uses the same adjective as for Adelaide, which is rather 'beautiful'} residence in Adelaide. {He refers to assembling a prefabricated house but I am not sure 'assemble' is quite applicable to houses}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:33.39,0:20:38.40,Default,,0,0,0,,So that, once I buy a sizeable plot, \Nwe could see it turn into a magnificent farmland.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:44.84,0:20:46.51,Default,,0,0,0,,That concludes my address.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:47.01,0:20:49.41,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, shall we finally eat?
Dialogue: 0,0:20:55.92,0:20:56.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Here.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:02.62,0:21:03.59,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿Here you go, Ben.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:07.66,0:21:12.40,Default,,0,0,0,,While sleeping in that barrel, what may happen to you in the dead of night? You never know.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:12.40,0:21:14.03,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿What may happen to me?
Dialogue: 0,0:21:14.80,0:21:16.77,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿Maybe spirits of the dead will rise? {Maybe ghosts start haunting?}{Current variant makes a pun with line 262}
Dialogue: 0,0:21:18.31,0:21:19.67,Default,,0,0,0,,You're such a buffoon.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:23.71,0:21:30.45,Default,,0,0,0,,Wanna know for real? This place is still full of wild dogs. \NThey look like wolves and really are ghastly{fellows}.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:30.45,0:21:31.02,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿Liar.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:31.02,0:21:31.82,Default,,0,0,0,,It's true!
Dialogue: 0,0:21:33.72,0:21:34.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, well, well? {﻿See? ﻿See? ﻿See?}
Dialogue: 0,0:21:35.86,0:21:40.36,Default,,0,0,0,,You really are a buffoon. \NThat is Mr. Pettywell's black dog.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:45.33,0:21:46.63,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿That is bad manners!
Dialogue: 0,0:21:47.43,0:21:49.64,Default,,0,0,0,,I have an urgent message for brother.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:50.10,0:21:51.14,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿What?
Dialogue: 0,0:21:51.14,0:21:55.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Regardless of what you say to Lucy-May, she is determined to sleep in the barrel.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:58.38,0:21:59.38,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿Suit yourself!
Dialogue: 0,0:22:49.43,0:22:55.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Mosh! Mosh, what is the matter? \NWe don't want you to be crushed. Go back to the basket.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:11.99,0:23:12.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Sis!
Dialogue: 0,0:23:12.75,0:23:13.59,Default,,0,0,0,,What is it?
Dialogue: 0,0:23:13.59,0:23:17.19,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿Wake up! A strange animal \Nstopped by to watch us just now!
Dialogue: 0,0:23:17.19,0:23:18.53,Default,,0,0,0,,Strange animal?
Dialogue: 0,0:23:18.53,0:23:22.20,Default,,0,0,0,,It resembled a rabbit somehow, \Nbut an enormous one!
Dialogue: 0,0:23:22.20,0:23:24.40,Default,,0,0,0,,﻿It was hop-hopping on two legs!
Dialogue: 0,0:23:24.40,0:23:29.20,Default,,0,0,0,,So a rabbit after all?\NGo back to sleep soon, Lucy-May.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:31.87,0:23:34.78,Default,,0,0,0,,So it's some kind of rabbit, huh?
Dialogue: 0,0:23:37.41,0:23:45.92,Default,,0,0,0,,We later found out the animal my little sister Lucy-May saw was an animal, only inhabiting Australia, which is kangaroo.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:46.80,0:23:52.29,Default,,0,0,0,,We never had any idea such an outlandish animal \Ncan even exist somewhere.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:05.21,0:24:10.54,Default,,0,0,0,,On our way back home from the water spring, \Nwe found this absolutely adorable and docile animal.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:10.54,0:24:15.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Next time in Lucy-May of the Southern Rainbow: \NCute Fellow. Join us again!
Comment: 0,0:24:23.21,0:24:27.21,Sign,,0,0,0,,[Mori e Oide]
